  "prompt": "What is the lowest temperature to leave a thermostat so that the pipes don't freeze?",
  "response": "To prevent pipes from freezing, it's generally recommended to keep your thermostat set to at least 55 degrees Fahrenheit (around 13 degrees Celsius). This temperature provides enough warmth to help ensure your home's pipes stay above the freezing point. However, you may need to increase the temperature if your home has poor insulation or is in an extremely cold climate. It's also important to insulate any exposed pipes and open cabinet doors under sinks to allow warmer air to circulate around plumbing.",
